Human1a:
A patient requires an urgent injection. While getting the injection ready, the nurse is uncertain whether the patient has fully understood the potential side effects. However, the nurse proceeds.



​The nurse’s action ensures the patient’s well-being but contravenes the patient’s autonomy (no informed consent).



Please rate your level of agreement/ disagreement with the nurse’s behavior.
Human1b:
A patient requires an urgent injection. While getting the injection ready, the nurse is uncertain whether the patient has fully understood the potential side effects. The nurse delays the injection and clearly informs the patient about the risks. 

 

The nurse’s action ensures the patient’s autonomy (informed consent) but endangers the patient’s well-being.



 Please rate your level of agreement/ disagreement with the nurse’s behavior.
Human2a:
The nurse urgently requires a medication for a patient (P1). It is stored in one of the examination rooms, currently occupied by another patient (P2) who is undressed for a physical check-up. Nonetheless, the nurse enters in order to get the medication.



​By doing so, the nurse ensures patient P1’s well-being but violates patient P2’s privacy.

 

Please rate your level of agreement/ disagreement with the nurse’s behavior.
Human2b:
The nurse urgently requires a medication for a patient (P1). It is stored in one of the examination rooms, currently occupied by another patient (P2) who is undressed for a physical check-up. The nurse waits outside until patient P2 leaves the room. 

 

By doing so, the nurse ensures patient P2’s privacy but endangers patient P1’s well-being.

 

Please rate your level of agreement/ disagreement with the nurse’s behavior.
Human3a:
There are two patients with the same condition. However, one of them is distressed due to the necessity to stay in the hospital overnight. The nurse decides to spend more time with the troubled patient. 

 

Thus, the nurse ensures the distressed patient’s well-being but neglects the rule that all patients should receive equal attention.

 

Please rate your level of agreement/ disagreement with the nurse’s behavior.
Human3b:
There are two patients with the same condition. However, one of them is more distressed due to the necessity to stay in the hospital overnight. The nurse decides to spend the same amount of time with each patient.



​Thus, the nurse ensures that all patients should receive equal attention but endangers the distressed patient’s well-being.

 

Please rate your level of agreement/ disagreement with the nurse’s behavior.
Human4a:
Shortly after a lung surgery, a nurse encounters the patient smoking a cigarette. The nurse explains him the risks of smoking in his condition, but the patient ignores the advice and refuses to stop. The nurse takes the cigarettes away from the patient and disposes of them.



​By doing so, the nurse ensures the patient’s well-being but violates the patient’s autonomy.


Please rate your level of agreement/ disagreement with the nurse’s behavior.
Human4b:
Shortly after a lung surgery, a nurse encounters the patient smoking a cigarette. The nurse explains him the risks of smoking in his condition, but the patient ignores the advice and refuses to stop. The nurse takes no further action.



​By doing so, the nurse respects the patient’s autonomy but endangers the patient’s well-being.



Please rate your level of agreement/ disagreement with the nurse’s behavior.
Human5a:
A patient requires to be monitored during his sleep. As the patient occasionally talks and cries in her/his sleep, she/he is reluctant to be monitored. The nurse ignores her/his concerns and enters the room after the patient has fallen asleep.



​The nurse’s action ensures the patient’s well-being but breaches the patient’s privacy.



Please rate your level of agreement/ disagreement with the nurse’s behavior.
Human5b:
A patient requires to be monitored during his sleep. As the patient occasionally talks and cries in her/his sleep, she/he is reluctant to be monitored, and the nurse refrains from doing so.

 

The nurse’s action ensures the patient’s privacy but endangers the patient’s well-being.



Please rate your level of agreement/ disagreement with the nurse’s behavior.
Human6a:
The nurse discovers that a patient passes on an expensive medication to one of her/his children. The child suffers from an early stage of the same disease, but does not yet qualify to receive this treatment. The nurse does not report this incident.



​By doing so the nurse ensures the child’s well-being but acts against a fair and just distribution of the treatment.



Please rate your level of agreement/ disagreement with the nurse’s behavior.
Human6b:
The nurse discovers that a patient passes on an expensive medication to one of her/his children. The child suffers from an early stage of the same disease, but does not yet qualify to receive this treatment. The nurse reports this incident.



​By doing so the nurse ensures a fair and just distribution of the medication but endangers the child’s well-being.



Please rate your level of agreement/ disagreement with the nurse’s behavior.
Human7a:
A patient suffers from a disease that causes severe physical pain and often results in the patient's death. The only available treatment causes additional distress and has only a marginal chance for success. The patient decides that undergoing the treatment would not be a life worth living and refuses treatment. The responsible doctor is convinced that even though the chances are small, the patient should not give up on life. The doctor instructs the nurse to carry out the treatment secretly and the nurse complies.



​By doing so the nurse ensures the patient’s well-being but ignores the patient’s autonomy.



Please rate your level of agreement/ disagreement with the nurse’s behavior.
Human7b:
A patient suffers from a disease that causes severe physical pain and often results in the patient's death. The only available treatment causes additional distress and has only a marginal chance for success. The patient decides that undergoing the treatment would not be a life worth living and refuses treatment. The responsible doctor is convinced that even though the chances are small, the patient should not give up on life. The doctor instructs the nurse to carry out the treatment secretly but the nurse refuses to comply.

Please rate your level of agreement/ disagreement with the nurse’s behavior.
Human8a:
An elderly patient is diagnosed with a terminal disease, leaving her/him little time to live. The patient decides not to inform her/his family as she/he does not want them to be worried. Nevertheless, the nurse notifies them, so that the patient can spend her/his last days amongst close family.



​By doing so the nurse promotes the patient’s well-being but breaches patient confidentiality.



Please rate your level of agreement/ disagreement with the nurse’s behavior.
Human8b:
An elderly patient is diagnosed with a terminal disease, leaving her/him little time to live. The patient decides not to inform her/his family as she/he does not want them to be worried. The nurse does not notify them, even though that means for the patient to spend her/his last days alone without the family.



​By doing so the nurse protects the patient confidentiality but compromises the patient’s well-being.



Please rate your level of agreement/ disagreement with the nurse’s behavior.

A doctor asks the nurse to add a patient to the waiting list for an organ transplant, although the patient does not yet need it. The intention is that by the time the patient will urgently require the organ, she/he will be amongst the next scheduled recipients. The nurse registers the patient.



​By doing so the nurse ensures the patient’s well-being but hinders the fair and just distribution of the organ donation program.

This questionnaire was the hardest I ever had to answer. Information provided on the different cases is not sufficient to make general statements possible. There are multiple factors which - if provided - could lead to me rating some situations completely differently from the way I have done. As an example, I cite the case where the nurse takes away the patient's cigarettes: was the patient smoking in the hospital or in the presence of children or other patients? If so, the nurse was completely justified. On the other hand, if the patient was alone and outside, the nurse was wrong, because patients should be free to ignore their doctor's advice. The nurse could have informed the doctor, however.

An interesting problem was brought up in a Brown Bag I recently attended, regarding a person who had moved to
the new HR staffing unit. Apparently, her department had not planned well for her departure, as her workload was
not adequately distributed to new people, and work wasn't getting done. Existing departments need to understand the
impact staff relocation and restructuring will have for them, and do some "succession planning" to ensure smooth
transitions. When staff who have traditionally been in an area and handled a particular job suddenly move to a SSC,
the rest of us who have depended on that person may be left without a valuable, trusted and knowledgeable resource.
Who will handle what that person did? Who is our new contact person in that area? This is just part of the growing
pains of the process, but the more aware department chairs are (mine happens to be very well aware of the situation)
the better department scan plan for restructuring
